Text mining (TM)

  • As the name suggests, text mining is a particular type of data mining technique -the mining of text-

Information retrieval (IR)

An Information retrieval system conssits of 3 basic elements:

  1. A set of documents
  2. A query
  3. A relevance metric

Goal: Sorting the set of documents according to their relevance to the query in question

The non digital reference information system par excellence is the library of Congress system

  • set of documents: books
  • query: searching for a specific theme/book
  • relevance: matching books with themes through a unique index

The nowadays reference digital infromation system: Google search engine!

  • set of documents: web sites on the internet
  • query: your words of search
  • relevance: page rank -and other algorithms-

Bag of words

There are a lot of techniques on how to measure relevance on an IR system, the simplest and most common of these is called bag of words. The idea is to take each word on a sentence/document as independent from the order in which they appear, and so we will need to break apart the orderâ¦

With this technique you have to tokenize all the words that you have -set of documents and query- how to tokenize them could be done in different ways though, again the simplest way is to tokenize by word.

The standard process for doing text mining with bag of words consists on the following steps:

  1. Eliminate accents and punctuation marks why?
  2. Eliminate numbers (if that make sense in your IR system)
  3. Change all letters to lower
  4. Eliminate stopwords why?
    • english
    • spanish
  5. Tokenization
  6. Apply stemming \(\rightarrow\) heuristic process for eliminating plurals, and simplify words. There are a lot of algorithms to do stemming, each one is particular for the language of use (optional):
    • Porter for english
    • Spanish
  7. Apply lemmatization \(\rightarrow\) formal linguistic process to get the lemma or root of a word. This algorithms require from linguists (optional).

TF-IDF

Term Frequency Inverse Doucment Frequency is the most common algorithm for measuring relevance on a IR system.

\[tf\_idf_t=tf \cdot log_{10}\frac{N}{df}\]

Where:

  • \(tf\): Term frequency
  • \(N\): Number of documents in the set
  • \(df\): Document frequency

Letâs try some values to understand IDF

  • Suppose we have a set of 100 documents and a token -word- appears on every document on the setâ¦ its IDF would be 0! \(\rightarrow\) the word is no relevant if it appears in all documentsâ¦
  • Suppose we have a set of 100 documents and a token appears only on 2 of themâ¦ its IDF would be 3.912023
  • Suppose we have a set of 100 documents and a token appears on 30 of themâ¦ its IDF would be 1.2039728
  • Suppose we have a set of 1000 documents and a token appears only on 2 of themâ¦ its IDF would be 6.2146081
  • Suppose we have a set of 100000 documents and a token appears on 100 of themâ¦ its IDF would be 6.9077553

Can you see the pattern?

In case thereâs more than one token on the query:

\[tf\_idf{q,d}=\sum_{t \in q} tf\_idf_{t,d}\]

Process

  1. Clean the documents with the standard process
  2. Build a Term Document Matrix (TDM) filling just the term column -set of all the tokens obtained from the previous step- Do you think it matters if we âstoreâ them in alphabetical order?
  3. Fill the Term Document Matrix (TDM) with the frequency of appereance of each token on each document of the set
Term Doc 1 Doc 2 Doc 3
something 0 12 0
else 0 0 2

(you can build also a DTMâ¦ but is more common to have a TDM)

  1. Calculate the document frequency for each term on the query
  2. Calculate the IDF for each term on the TDM
  3. Calculate the TF-IDF for each element on the TDM matrix
  4. Calculate the TF-IDF for each term on the query
  5. Sum each TF-IDF of each document and sort them ascendently
  6. Sort the set of documents according to the relevance obtained in step 8

Business case

Problem

  • An editorial company wants to tag all of its digital content, they (used to) have 13 different brands generating media content from sports to business and everything in between.
  • The length of the context varies significatively from brand to brand: ~20 words to ~5,000 words (special investigations)
  • The editorial company has a taxonomy -based on the international standard IPTC- of the themes that they normally write about
    • ~3,942 tags
    • 5 levels of abstraction

BM25 Okapi Best Match

  • 3 variables
    • Documents length
    • Query length
    • Frequency of the term on the query
  • 3 parameters
    • \(k1\) the effect of the term frequency on the document tunning
    • \(k2\) the effect of the term frequency on the query tunning
    • \(b\) the effect of the document length of the data set tunning

\[ \sum_{i\in Q} log\frac{(r_{i} + 0.5)(N-n_{i}-R+r_{i}+0.5)}{(n_{i}-r_{i}+0.5)(R-r_{i}+0.5)}\cdot \frac{(k_{1}+1)f_{i}}{(K+f_{i})} \cdot \frac{(k_{2}+1)qf_{i}}{k_{2}+qf_{i}}\]

\[K=k_{1}\left((1-b)+b\cdot\frac{dl}{avgdl}\right)\]

Term 1

\[log\frac{(r_{i} + 0.5)(N-n_{i}-R+r_{i}+0.5)}{(n_{i}-r_{i}+0.5)(R-r_{i}+0.5)}\]

Term 2

\[\frac{(k_{1}+1)f_{i}}{(K+f_{i})}\] \[K=k_{1}\left((1-b)+b\cdot\frac{dl}{avgdl}\right)\]

\(k1=[0.0,2.0]\) valor tÃ­pico \(\rightarrow\) 1.2 * \(b=[0.0,1.0]\) valor tÃ­pico \(\rightarrow\) 0.75*
